Commentary: OUT! LBW! Another appeal for LBW and this time, up goes the finger! The clock ticks and Devon Conway does opt for a review to challenge the on-field decision. Seam-up delivery, on a fuller length from around the stumps, angling on the off and middle channel. Devon Conway takes a half stride forward to push to the mid off region but plays over the line as the ball nips back in with the angle. UltraEdge shows no bat involved and Ball Tracking comes up with three reds. OUT. Not quite sure why Conway reviewed it because as soon as the DRS was loading up, he had already started to walk back to the dressing room. Latham initially had signaled from the non-striker's end that the point of contact might be outside the line of the off-pole and hence, Conway decided to review it. New Zealand burn a review and more importantly, an early wicket. India get their first breakthrough and Akash Deep is all pumped up. New Zealand are 15/1.

Commentary: OUT! TAKEN! What a magnificent catch by Rohit Sharma at the first slip. An absolute stunner from the Indian skipper. Washington Sundar bowls from over the stumps and flattens the trajectory, bowls it on a good length, around middle and off channel. Daryl Mitchell is quick to rock back and squats at it to guide it through the short third region but is beaten by the pace and just tries to guide it with soft hands. Opens the bat face and ends up slicing it off the outer half. The ball goes flat and low towards the first slip. Commentary: OUT! LBW! A huge appeal for LBW and the umpire raises his finger! Ajaz Patel removes the nightwatchman in the very first delivery and New Zealand has sneaked back into the game now. Patel comes from around the stumps and lands it on a fullish length, it lands, grips and turns a fraction away from the batter. Mohammed Siraj lunges ahead to defend it out but plays inside the line of the ball and wears it on the back pad. Nothing on UltraEdge and Ball Tracking comes up with three reds. India burn a crucial review and this will be part of the debate as well. Ajaz Patel is on a HAT TRICK now. India has slipped to 78/3 after a decent start.

Commentary: OUT! DEAR, OH DEAR! RUN OUT! Almost a reminiscence of the Cheteshwar Pujara dismissal against Australia at The Adelaide Oval in the first Test in 2018, when Pat Cummins scored a direct hit from mid on to catch Pujara short at the bowling end. The batter and opposition are different this time but the result and the subsequent questions regarding the run precisely the same. In both cases, the call was questionable from the batter and the fielder was a fast bowler. Was the call made probably because Kohli felt that Henry might have been resting on his heels? And basically, was this run necessary at this stage of the day? Not sure. Kohli perishes too after a boundary. This is going from bad to worse now for India. A run out just at the brink of Stumps and Virat Kohli is absolutely animated with himself. Fuller in length, and at the stumps. Kohli got on the front foot and pushed it to mid on, calling through for a quick single. Matt Henry, at mid on was quick to pick and throw in a motion and scored a terrific direct hit at the non-striker's end. Kohli was compelled to put in a full-length dive to get home. The Kiwis started to celebrate and the decision was referred upstairs. The TV umpire confirms that Kohli's bat was just a foot outside the crease when the stumps were hit. It was Kohli's call so no one else could be really blamed. Heartbreaking last 15 minutes or so for India as they have now slipped from a comfortable 78/1 to a precarious 84/4. On the other hand, terrific from New Zealand to keep on fighting till the very end.
Default_Commentary: 18.3: Rachin Ravindra to Virat Kohli, OUT! run out (Matt Henry).

Commentary: OUT! A huge appeal for LBW and up goes the finger. Sodhi provides a huge crucial breakthrough for New Zealand. Rishabh Pant has a chat with Gill and just with a couple of seconds remaining on the timer, he signals the 'T' and challenges the on-field decision. Sodhi comes from around the stumps and lands fairly outside off. It pitches, grips and stays low and prodigiously turns back into the left-hander. Rishabh Pant goes on the back foot to work it to the leg side but gets beaten by the turn and lack of bounce. The ball passes close to the bat and pings his front pad. UltraEdge shows no spike and the Ball Tracking comes up with the ball hitting the leg stump on the umpire's call. OUT IT IS! Michael Gough, the umpire, gets it right yet again this time and this just might be the breakthrough the Kiwis were looking for. A celebration in unison from them as Pant departs on almost a run-a-ball 60. India are 180/5 down now, trailing by 55 runs.

Commentary: OUT! 6TH FIVE-WICKET HAUL FOR AJAZ PATEL, ALL IN THE SUBCONTINENT! And he continues to weave his magic at Wankhede. India are 9 wickets down now with a very thin lead at their helm. Patel stays around the stumps and loops it up on a fullish length, it lands, grips, bounces and turns sharply away from the batter. Ravichandran Ashwin is drawn forward and looks to push it through the off side but that excessive turn and bounce takes the outside edge of his willow and Daryl Mitchell with his safe pair of hands takes a regulation catch at the first slip. Ravichandran Ashwin departs on 6 off 13 balls and India have now slipped down badly against Ajaz Patel.

Commentary: OUT! RUN OUT! An anti-climatic end to the Indian innings! Ajaz Patel lands this short again and around off, Washington Sundar steers it away through point and runs the single very quickly thinking there is a chance of a second run but he gives up that idea. However, Akash Deep is a bit late turn back, and Rachin Ravindra quickly charges onto the ball and throws it right at the top of the stumps where Tom Blundell collects and breaks the stumps in a flash. Akash Deep did not want to put a dive in and tries to drag his bat inside but the replay shows that he is short of his crease. Sundar is disappointed as he was looking good to extend this lead even further but now India have been bowled out for 263 runs.

Commentary: OUT! TAKEN! Oh dear oh dear! We have another twist in the tale in this game, Rishabh Pant is not happy with this decision but has to walk back. Ajaz Patel slows it up a bit, full and on off, turns in sharply with bounce, Rishabh Pant uses his feet and looks to defend but the ball passes close to the inside edge and pops up, Tom Blundell, the keeper gets forward and completes the catch. Another appeal for bat-pad, but turned down again! Tom Latham is desperate here and decides to take the review. UltraEdge shows a spike when the bat hits his pad, but there is also a spike when the ball is close to the bat and there is no gap in the replay. The third umpire overturns the on-field call and there is complete silence around the ground. Pant cannot believe it one bit, and has an animated chat with the on-field umpire, Michael Gough. But, it is done and dusted as the decision has been made and he goes back with the slowest walks to the dressing room, departing after 64 off 57 and this is anyone's game now. Boos all around the Wankhede as the controller of the game is gone. Ajaz Patel gets his 7th five-wicket haul, and each of them has come in the subcontinent. New Zealand can now sense history in the making as they are just 3 wickets away from executing a clean sweep.

Commentary: OUT! KNOCKED HIM OVER! NEW ZEALAND BLANK INDIA OUT IN THIS 3-MATCH TEST SERIES AND EXECUTE A DOMINATING CLEAN SWEEP! History has been scripted at the Wankhede Stadium and probably the greatest Test series win in the history of New Zealand cricket. And this is the first ever time when India has been whitewashed in a 3-match Test series on their home soil. Absolute pin-drop silence in the stadium but exactly contradictory scenes in the visitors' camp as their joy knows no bounds. Coming to the delivery, Ajaz Patel bowls it from over the stumps, and tosses this one up. Full in length, outside off, and it lands right on the rough and spins back in viciously. Washington Sundar sits down to access the slog sweep but the turn gets the better of him. He gets no bat on it and the ball disturbs the furniture. Ajaz Patel finish off with a spectacular 6-for but this has been a complete team performance by the Blackcaps. They win this series by 3-0.
